Hello?

216
00:13:47,873 --> 00:13:49,942
[laughs] Hello? Excuse me?

217
00:13:50,112 --> 00:13:52,580
You're not Patrick Sullivan, are you?

218
00:13:52,752 --> 00:13:56,381
- You are? No.
- May I help you?

219
00:13:56,552 --> 00:14:00,784
- I hope so. Is this 230133rd Street?
- Yes. It is.

220
00:14:00,952 --> 00:14:04,580
I'm looking for someone who lives here
by the unlikely name, Patrick Sullivan.

221
00:14:04,751 --> 00:14:08,380
- Patrick.
- [speaking foreign language]

222
00:14:11,551 --> 00:14:14,986
Keep going, tall lady! Keep going!

223
00:14:24,790 --> 00:14:26,381
Excuse me?

224
00:14:26,549 --> 00:14:30,383
Excuse me, sir? Officer?

225
00:14:31,789 --> 00:14:33,586
- Hello!
- [yelling]

226
00:14:33,749 --> 00:14:36,547
- [screaming]
- Hey. Hey, I'm sorry...

227
00:14:36,709 --> 00:14:41,145
No, no, no! That's fine. Um, can you
tell me how I can find Patrick Sullivan?

228
00:14:49,827 --> 00:14:52,785
- We couldn't get that lady out.
- She weighed 500 pounds!

229
00:14:52,827 --> 00:14:55,739
- She knocked you with her skillet.
- Frying pan.

230
00:14:55,907 --> 00:14:57,659
- Patrick?
- Yeah. Ah!

231
00:14:57,827 --> 00:15:00,102
You won't believe this.
That home-wrecking lady

232
00:15:00,267 --> 00:15:01,824
from the radio walked in here.

233
00:15:01,986 --> 00:15:03,783
- I believe you.
- Can I help you?

234
00:15:03,946 --> 00:15:06,414
- What's she doin'?
- Looking for Patrick Sullivan.

235
00:15:06,586 --> 00:15:09,384
- I was told he might be here.
- Right over there.

236
00:15:09,546 --> 00:15:11,537
- She looked over.
- What are you havin'?

237
00:15:11,706 --> 00:15:14,742
- Um, whatever he's having.
- I'll bring it right over.

238
00:15:14,905 --> 00:15:16,941
It's walkin' right this way.

239
00:15:17,105 --> 00:15:19,494
- It's takin' its coat off.
- How do you do?

240
00:15:19,665 --> 00:15:23,135
It just looked at me again.
It's comin' over here.

241
00:15:23,305 --> 00:15:26,216
It's comin' right for me.
What does it want?

242
00:15:28,384 --> 00:15:31,217
Patrick Sullivan?
You're not an easy man to find.

243
00:15:31,384 --> 00:15:35,013
- I'm Emma Lloyd.
- It thinks I'm you. Help me out.

244
00:15:35,184 --> 00:15:38,095
Hey, I, uh... I dropped my chalk.
I'm Patrick Sullivan.

245
00:15:38,263 --> 00:15:42,097
- This is my opponent, Larry Berlson.
- Oh! Mr Sullivan. Mr Berlson.

246
00:15:42,263 --> 00:15:44,538
How do you do?
I'm here for the oddest reason.

247
00:15:44,703 --> 00:15:46,295
- We all are.
- Here you are.

248
00:15:46,463 --> 00:15:48,260
- Mine?
- Mind if I interrupt?

249
00:15:48,423 --> 00:15:50,333
- Knock yourself out.
- I didn't mean...

250
00:15:50,502 --> 00:15:51,651
- Don't play?
- Yes.

251
00:15:51,822 --> 00:15:54,052
Then you're stripes.
Down the hatch.

252
00:15:54,222 --> 00:15:58,340
- No, no, Mr Sullivan. I'm here to...
- You don't drink? You don't play pool?

253
00:15:58,502 --> 00:16:02,892
- Perhaps I can get you an herbal tea?
- [laughter]

254
00:16:04,581 --> 00:16:06,253
Nine in the corner.

255
00:16:09,021 --> 00:16:11,012
- [all exclaim]
- We need another round.

256
00:16:11,181 --> 00:16:13,899
Mr Sullivan. Something
very unfortunate has happened,

257
00:16:14,060 --> 00:16:16,972
- and it could make a mess of my life.
- I'm sorry to hear that.

258
00:16:17,140 --> 00:16:19,495
- It's certainly not your fault.
- It's your shot.

259
00:16:19,660 --> 00:16:22,697
Um, all right. [laughs]
Well, how can I explain?

260
00:16:22,860 --> 00:16:26,408
You see, um, uh,
I'm about to be married.

261
00:16:26,579 --> 00:16:28,456
- [all exclaim]
- That is too bad!

262
00:16:28,619 --> 00:16:31,850
Congratulations on the other thing.
We got a bride in our midst.

263
00:16:32,019 --> 00:16:34,169
- [all shouting]
- [applause]

264
00:16:34,339 --> 00:16:36,488
Thank you. That won't be necessary.

265
00:16:36,658 --> 00:16:40,128
It's necessary. I feel a toast
coming on. Wait a second.

266
00:16:40,298 --> 00:16:42,368
- I know you.
- Excuse me?

267
00:16:42,538 --> 00:16:45,132
<i>Yeah, yeah.
Real Love With Dr Emma Lloyd.</i>

268
00:16:45,298 --> 00:16:49,131
- You're that lady I hear on the radio.
- Yes, of course. You found me out.

269
00:16:49,297 --> 00:16:52,687
- Have you ever been on television?
- Um, no, but I have a book coming out.

270
00:16:52,857 --> 00:16:55,929
- I love television.
- My girlfriend never misses your show.

271
00:16:56,097 --> 00:16:58,565
Oh, well, has it been
helpful in your relationship?

272
00:16:58,737 --> 00:17:02,695
[laughing] Oh, you have no idea.
It's completely changed our lives!

273
00:17:02,856 --> 00:17:06,405
- Oh, really? That is so nice to hear.
- Yeah. Tony! Here you go.

274
00:17:06,576 --> 00:17:09,249
- To the bride and ever-changing life!
- To the bride!

275
00:17:09,416 --> 00:17:12,054
[all] To the bride!

276
00:17:13,215 --> 00:17:17,049
Mr Sullivan, as I was saying,
you see, I'm about to be married.

277
00:17:17,215 --> 00:17:20,571
Be careful. Forty-three per cent
of marriages end in divorce.

278
00:17:20,735 --> 00:17:23,613
That's right. It's all
about picking the right partner.

279
00:17:23,774 --> 00:17:26,732
- So true. It's so true.
- In order to do that, my fiancé,

280
00:17:26,894 --> 00:17:29,124
Richard, and I,
need a license from New York...

281
00:17:29,294 --> 00:17:33,333
- Richard from dispatch? Asshole.
- So on an otherwise lovely morning,

282
00:17:33,494 --> 00:17:35,688
- we go to city hall...
- To Emma and Richie!

283
00:17:35,853 --> 00:17:38,845
- [all cheering]
- Richard!

284
00:17:39,013 --> 00:17:41,607
- And I don't want any more.
- Hey, you're right.

285
00:17:41,773 --> 00:17:44,606
Don't want Richie to see
you hammered before your wedding.

286
00:17:44,773 --> 00:17:46,809
Tony! Give me
that herbal tea over here.

287
00:17:46,973 --> 00:17:49,770
- Herbal tea, coming up!
- [all shouting]

288
00:17:49,932 --> 00:17:54,528
- [laughs]
- Very funny, Mr Sullivan. Very funny.

289
00:17:54,692 --> 00:17:57,081
- I'll have you know I don't get drunk.
- You don't?

290
00:17:57,252 --> 00:18:00,288
No. My father taught me a good trick
to hold one's liquor.

291
00:18:00,451 --> 00:18:03,045
You simply recite
the presidents' names in order.

292
00:18:03,211 --> 00:18:05,771
- Out loud?
- Forwards or backwards?

293
00:18:05,931 --> 00:18:09,321
Watch and learn, gentlemen.
To Washington, Adams, Jefferson,

294
00:18:09,491 --> 00:18:11,288
Madison and Monroe.

295
00:18:12,530 --> 00:18:14,361
- Carter!
- [all] Carter!

296
00:18:14,530 --> 00:18:17,647
- Reagan!
- [all] Reagan!

297
00:18:17,810 --> 00:18:19,562
- Bush!
- [all] Bush!

298
00:18:19,730 --> 00:18:22,403
Do you think maybe we
should pour you into a cab?

299
00:18:22,570 --> 00:18:25,003
- Maybe your fiancé's worried.
- Oh! That's right!

300
00:18:25,169 --> 00:18:27,558
That is exactly what
I came to talk to you about.

301
00:18:27,729 --> 00:18:29,640
- OK.
- Yes, Mr Sullivan,

302
00:18:29,809 --> 00:18:32,084
- it seems we're married.
- Come again?

303
00:18:32,249 --> 00:18:36,036
We... are married!

304
00:18:36,208 --> 00:18:38,722
- I thought you were marrying Richie.
- Exactly!

305
00:18:38,888 --> 00:18:40,287
- I'm over here.
- Right!

306
00:18:40,448 --> 00:18:44,726
Uh, yes, it seems that we,
I mean we,

307
00:18:44,888 --> 00:18:48,084
are victims of a glitch in some
computer, somewhere, somehow,

308
00:18:48,247 --> 00:18:50,807
I don't know, has married us.

309
00:18:50,967 --> 00:18:54,357
- A glitch?
- Mm-hm. I'll say. A big one.

310
00:18:54,527 --> 00:19:00,044
- [laughs] Oh, boy.
- So, um, if, um, you'd just be...

311
00:19:00,206 --> 00:19:03,164
...so kind as
to sign these papers I'd...

312
00:19:03,326 --> 00:19:05,556
[all groan]

313
00:19:05,726 --> 00:19:07,876
- Ow!
- [all groan]

314
00:19:10,526 --> 00:19:13,358
Washington, Madison, Adamson...

315
00:19:13,525 --> 00:19:16,358
- Are you a fireman?
- Indeed, I am.

316
00:19:16,525 --> 00:19:18,993
I always liked you guys.

317
00:19:21,805 --> 00:19:24,159
Lights are out now.

318
00:19:30,204 --> 00:19:31,193
[grunts]

319
00:19:56,842 --> 00:19:59,401
- [Emma grunts]
- Sorry about that.

320
00:20:20,560 --> 00:20:22,356
[Patrick whispers] Oh! Ouch!

321
00:20:28,199 --> 00:20:31,236
[cell phone rings]

322
00:21:03,596 --> 00:21:05,985
[moaning]

323
00:21:09,915 --> 00:21:14,511
<i>- [¶¶ A.R. Rahman: Yaro Yarodi]
- [moaning]</i>

324
00:21:16,715 --> 00:21:18,626
[screams]

325
00:21:21,994 --> 00:21:24,986
Hello? [whispers] Oh, no!

326
00:21:25,154 --> 00:21:27,793
Oh, no! Oh, no!

327
00:21:29,354 --> 00:21:30,833
[gasps]

328
00:21:33,553 --> 00:21:36,021
Oh, my God!

329
00:21:36,193 --> 00:21:38,707
Oh, my God!

330
00:21:38,873 --> 00:21:40,386
Oh!

331
00:21:43,313 --> 00:21:45,144
Oh, my God.

332
00:21:45,313 --> 00:21:46,791
[screams]

333
00:21:54,352 --> 00:21:55,705
[speaks foreign language]

334
00:22:02,711 --> 00:22:03,780
Oh!

335
00:22:11,390 --> 00:22:12,379
Excuse me.

336
00:22:19,590 --> 00:22:23,821
- Good morning, Dr Lloyd.
- Good morning. Wait!

337
00:22:23,989 --> 00:22:26,025
- Someone had a rough night.
- Oh, yeah.

338
00:22:29,189 --> 00:22:31,145
Excuse me.

339
00:22:35,228 --> 00:22:38,379
- Oh, my.
- I need the emergency outfit.

340
00:22:38,548 --> 00:22:40,106
- What?
- The emergency outfit!

341
00:22:40,268 --> 00:22:41,906
Outfit I keep for emergencies.

342
00:22:42,068 --> 00:22:44,787
Richard called six and a half times.
Last time he hung up.

343
00:22:44,947 --> 00:22:47,700
He was looking desperate.
Worried about Bollenbeckers?

344
00:22:47,867 --> 00:22:49,744
- Can you get him for me?
- On the phone?

345
00:22:49,907 --> 00:22:51,659
- Why do you do that?
- It's fun.

346
00:22:51,827 --> 00:22:54,341
- The outfit?
- Not here.

347
00:22:54,507 --> 00:22:55,656
- I had a date.
- Oh!

348
00:22:55,827 --> 00:22:57,976
You know we're not remotely
the same size?

349
00:22:58,146 --> 00:23:01,343
- Richard. Aspirin. Coffee.
- Oh, and your father's...

350
00:23:01,506 --> 00:23:05,181
- Now!
- Please hold. Richard, line one!

351
00:23:08,186 --> 00:23:12,144
Richard, sweetheart.
I am so sorry I didn't call.

352
00:23:12,305 --> 00:23:16,014
I was in Queens so I thought I'd stay at
my father's and go over wedding stuff.

353
00:23:16,185 --> 00:23:18,824
<i>- Why didn't you call?
- He brought you in this morning</i>

354
00:23:18,985 --> 00:23:21,418
- with your mom's dress.
- He brought me back in

355
00:23:21,584 --> 00:23:24,257
- with my mom's wedding dress.
- And your father's here.

356
00:23:24,424 --> 00:23:26,415
<i>- She knows it.
- What about Sullivan?</i>

357
00:23:26,584 --> 00:23:27,903
<i>- It's beautiful.
- Emma?</i>

358
00:23:28,064 --> 00:23:30,976
- Yes! I found Sullivan.
- Coffee, Wilder?

359
00:23:31,144 --> 00:23:32,462
- I'd love some.
- Aspirin?

360
00:23:32,623 --> 00:23:34,454
- I've got the papers.
- Welcome.

361
00:23:34,623 --> 00:23:36,136
- Not on me.
- [cell phone rings]

362
00:23:36,303 --> 00:23:37,975
- Coffee filters?
- I don't work here.

363
00:23:38,143 --> 00:23:40,737
I know they have to be notarised.
Can you get that?

364
00:23:40,903 --> 00:23:42,382
- Sure.
- Don't worry.

365
00:23:42,543 --> 00:23:47,172
You have enough on your plate without
having to worry about this. Don't...

366
00:23:47,342 --> 00:23:49,902
Emma, your husband would
like a few words with you.

367
00:23:50,062 --> 00:23:51,859
- [both] Who?
- Patrick Sullivan?

368
00:23:52,022 --> 00:23:54,536
<i>- ... have them on you?
- Sweetheart, can you, um?</i>

369
00:23:54,702 --> 00:23:57,454
Can you hold please? Not a word.

370
00:23:58,781 --> 00:24:00,658
<i>[Patrick] Hello? You there? Hello?</i>

371
00:24:00,821 --> 00:24:02,891
<i>- Ah! Mr Sullivan?
- Hey.</i>

372
00:24:03,061 --> 00:24:06,497
Let me get to the point. I left some
very important documents in your...

373
00:24:06,661 --> 00:24:09,333
- Richard! Phone!
- Uh, can you just hold on

374
00:24:09,500 --> 00:24:11,889
<i>- one second? Don't go away.
- Yeah.</i>

375
00:24:13,420 --> 00:24:16,696
Richard, sweetheart,
I am so sorry to keep you holding.

376
00:24:16,860 --> 00:24:19,454
<i>- What's going on?
- I'll explain at the cake tasting.</i>

377
00:24:19,620 --> 00:24:23,532
<i>- I can't. I'll meet you tonight.
- But you promised. All right.</i>

378
00:24:23,699 --> 00:24:27,533
- [phone rings]
- Husband! Cell!

379
00:24:27,699 --> 00:24:31,374
Oh! Mr Sullivan? Mr Sullivan!

380
00:24:31,539 --> 00:24:33,529
- Wilder, here.
- Mr Sullivan? Hello?

381
00:24:33,698 --> 00:24:36,576
- Your father on two.
- Gotta run, darling! See you later.

382
00:24:36,738 --> 00:24:39,855
- Gonna wait for your coffee?
- Nobody's got that kind of time.

383
00:24:40,018 --> 00:24:42,737
I don't know what
you're smirking about, Wilder.

384
00:24:42,898 --> 00:24:45,047
I'm just glad
to see you're having some fun.

385
00:24:45,217 --> 00:24:48,050
Does it look like I'm having fun?
Wait.

386
00:24:48,217 --> 00:24:51,892
You drove all the way in
just to bring Mom's dress?

387
00:24:52,057 --> 00:24:55,208
Actually, I was hoping
to lure you over to Bemelmans

388
00:24:55,377 --> 00:24:59,415
- for a banana split like the old days.
- Bemelmans has been closed for years.

389
00:24:59,576 --> 00:25:02,488
Ah, well, my timing's
always been a little off.

390
00:25:02,656 --> 00:25:05,295
- [phone rings]
- Don't keep your husbands waiting.

391
00:25:05,456 --> 00:25:08,128
- It's not what you think.
- I know.

392
00:25:08,295 --> 00:25:11,332
Mr Sullivan?
Thank you so much for calling back.

393
00:25:11,495 --> 00:25:13,292
- Excuse me?
- What do you want?

394
00:25:13,455 --> 00:25:16,015
- Car's downstairs. You're late.
- Mr Sullivan.

395
00:25:16,175 --> 00:25:18,211
<i>- Yes.
- Yes, about last night.</i>

396
00:25:18,375 --> 00:25:19,932
<i>- Yeah.
- What exactly happened?</i>

397
00:25:20,094 --> 00:25:23,848
<i>I tell you this, you do one hell
of a Riverdance. It was quite a night.</i>

398
00:25:24,014 --> 00:25:26,733
<i>- That doesn't sound like me.
- That wasn't the good part.</i>

399
00:25:26,894 --> 00:25:28,373
<i>- What do you mean?
- I'm here.</i>

400
00:25:28,534 --> 00:25:32,162
You're where?
Hey, I'm losing you. Hello?

401
00:25:32,333 --> 00:25:34,972
Can you hear me now?
Look, forget last night.

402
00:25:35,133 --> 00:25:38,091
What I want is a rather large stack
of papers I need you to sign.

403
00:25:38,253 --> 00:25:41,211
- I got 'em right here.
- You do! Thanks. You made my day.

404
00:25:41,373 --> 00:25:43,727
- Coffee?
- Thank you.

405
00:25:43,892 --> 00:25:46,690
- I know a notary not far from here.
- Right now?

406
00:25:46,852 --> 00:25:49,082
This appointment
took me three months to get.

407
00:25:49,252 --> 00:25:51,083
- Sounds important.
- Cake tasting.

408
00:25:51,252 --> 00:25:53,891
- Like I said, important stuff.
- It's the wedding cake,

409
00:25:54,052 --> 00:25:56,849
and she's Marilyn Hirschfield,
a respected cake maker.

410
00:25:57,011 --> 00:25:59,366
- These appointments are hard...
- I love cake!

411
00:25:59,531 --> 00:26:01,567
- What are you doing? Hey!
- Scoot over.

412
00:26:01,731 --> 00:26:05,963
- This cake is fantastic!
- Shh! Please, please. Be quiet.

413
00:26:06,131 --> 00:26:09,805
- Can I get another slice of this one?
- You've already tried the butter cream.

414
00:26:09,970 --> 00:26:13,087
It's my fiancée. She's on the fence
about the butter cream.

415
00:26:13,250 --> 00:26:14,808
- I am not.
- Have any milk?

416
00:26:14,970 --> 00:26:16,926
- Sure.
- After this, we go to the notary?

417
00:26:17,090 --> 00:26:20,445
- Yeah, absolutely. How much is this?
- It's free, sir.

418
00:26:20,609 --> 00:26:23,840
Bullshit! It's free!

419
00:26:24,009 --> 00:26:27,046
- [man] Here you are, sir.
- Here's my milk.

420
00:26:27,209 --> 00:26:30,883
- Would you like a sip?
- No, thank you. I'm not six.

421
00:26:31,048 --> 00:26:33,278
Holy crap! [laughs] Cake down.

422
00:26:33,448 --> 00:26:36,281
I need a spoon. Don't worry about it.
I got this.

423
00:26:36,448 --> 00:26:39,997
Here we have our dark Belgian chocolate
with vanilla mousse torte.

424
00:26:40,168 --> 00:26:41,999
- Thank you.
- It's awesome.

425
00:26:46,647 --> 00:26:49,445
Oh, my God! Do you know
if you mix these two together,

426
00:26:49,607 --> 00:26:51,882
it tastes like a Ring Ding!
You gotta try this.

427
00:26:52,047 --> 00:26:56,005
No, no, no. That's all right.
I'm not your baby. No, no, no, no, no!

428
00:26:56,166 --> 00:26:58,077
- Ah! Ah!
- No!

429
00:26:58,246 --> 00:26:59,679
- Mmm?
- Ah?

430
00:26:59,846 --> 00:27:04,044
- Mm. It's yummy.
- It's super-duper.

431
00:27:04,206 --> 00:27:08,881
Mm-hm. Um, may I, um... may I just
have one more glass of milk, please?

432
00:27:09,045 --> 00:27:11,843
Attagirl! Milk for my bride.
In fact, milks all around.

433
00:27:12,005 --> 00:27:13,677
Milks all around.

434
00:27:13,845 --> 00:27:16,643
- Hey, where you ladies from?
- Germany.

435
00:27:16,805 --> 00:27:18,715
Wow! You must really like cake.

436
00:27:18,884 --> 00:27:21,682
Yeah, you gotta try this,
and mix these two together.

437
00:27:21,844 --> 00:27:25,359
Hey, hey, can we get, uh, some
Ring Ding things for the gals over here?

438
00:27:25,524 --> 00:27:27,992
Darling, I am certain
everyone is being attended to.

439
00:27:28,164 --> 00:27:31,041
Baby, I got this covered.
Don't you worry about it.

440
00:27:31,203 --> 00:27:34,115
- Quite a handful you got there.
- That he is.

441
00:27:34,283 --> 00:27:38,196
Impulsive, unpredictable. You never
know what he's gonna do next.

442
00:27:38,363 --> 00:27:41,400
- Full of surprises.
- But that's the fun of it, isn't it?

443
00:27:41,563 --> 00:27:44,759
- Of course it is.
- It is, trust me.

444
00:27:44,922 --> 00:27:47,595
- Here you go, ladies.
- He reminds me of my husband

445
00:27:47,762 --> 00:27:50,993
when we first met. Everybody
thought we were a total mismatch,

446
00:27:51,162 --> 00:27:55,951
<i>but we had so much fun.
And we still do 25 years later.</i>

447
00:27:56,121 --> 00:27:58,760
Hey! What are you ladies
talkin' about over here?

448
00:27:58,921 --> 00:28:01,276
- Talking about the men in our lives.
- Ah, boys.

449
00:28:01,441 --> 00:28:04,592
- Never mind.
- How did you two meet?

450
00:28:06,200 --> 00:28:09,476
Oh, honey, you tell the story.
You tell it a lot better than I do.

451
00:28:09,640 --> 00:28:15,272
No, no, no, no, no. No, you tell it.
You're the good, uh, teller of it.

452
00:28:15,440 --> 00:28:17,635
- Please?
- All right, all right. Sure.

453
00:28:17,800 --> 00:28:21,508
- You ladies heard of pro wrestling?
- Stop! Kidder!

454
00:28:21,679 --> 00:28:23,556
Oh, he's such a kidder. Kidder.

455
00:28:23,719 --> 00:28:26,711
It was a, um, uh... a blind date.

456
00:28:26,879 --> 00:28:29,313
- Oh?
- Yeah, yeah, we were fixed up.

457
00:28:29,479 --> 00:28:31,833
Yes! Fixed up.
But not with each other.

458
00:28:31,998 --> 00:28:35,149
It was two separate blind dates
in the same bar.

459
00:28:35,318 --> 00:28:37,149
- Both goin' terribly.
- Horribly!

460
00:28:37,318 --> 00:28:39,388
Think about those people who set us up.

461
00:28:39,558 --> 00:28:41,594
- Susie and Allen.
- Susie and Allen.

462
00:28:41,757 --> 00:28:45,670
- What the hell did they know?
- I don't know. I guess he noticed me.

463
00:28:45,837 --> 00:28:48,954
Well, I mean, come on. Look at her.

464
00:28:49,117 --> 00:28:54,110
- A guy would have to be blind.
- Noticed me suffering on my bad date,

465
00:28:54,276 --> 00:28:58,428
and then the band started playing this
song, and it was my favourite song.

466
00:28:58,596 --> 00:29:03,750
And suddenly he was next to me and
he asked me to dance, and... I said yes.

467
00:29:06,195 --> 00:29:08,231
- What was the song?
- Song?

468
00:29:08,395 --> 00:29:11,228
- Mm-hm?
- Oh, yeah, the song.

469
00:29:11,395 --> 00:29:13,829
<i>- Oh.
- ¶ Over night scenes ¶</i>

470
00:29:13,995 --> 00:29:17,146
<i>¶ Dinner and wine
Saturday girls ¶</i>

471
00:29:17,315 --> 00:29:20,431
<i>¶ I was never in love
Never had the time ¶</i>

472
00:29:20,594 --> 00:29:23,904
<i>- Honey, Every Woman in the World.
- Every Woman in the World.</i>

473
00:29:24,074 --> 00:29:26,224
<i>¶ Laughing myself to sleep ¶</i>

474
00:29:26,394 --> 00:29:30,432
<i>¶ Waking up lonely
I needed someone to hold me ¶</i>

475
00:29:30,593 --> 00:29:31,662
<i>¶ Oh, oh, oh ¶</i>

476
00:29:31,833 --> 00:29:36,861
<i>[all] ¶ Girl, you're every woman
in the world to me ¶</i>

477
00:29:37,033 --> 00:29:39,672
<i>¶ You're my fantasy ¶</i>

478
00:29:39,833 --> 00:29:43,905
<i>- ¶ You're my reality ¶
- That's it! Uh, that's the song.</i>

479
00:29:51,072 --> 00:29:53,028
That was totally
off the top of my head.

480
00:29:53,191 --> 00:29:56,900
Known each other for two hours
and we already got a song.

481
00:29:57,071 --> 00:30:01,428
We don't have a song.
How long is this gonna take?

482
00:30:07,030 --> 00:30:09,021
[door buzzing]

483
00:30:10,630 --> 00:30:13,098
Emma Lloyd, Deepak Manaam Chaturvedi.

484
00:30:13,270 --> 00:30:15,465
- Mr Manaam Chater...
- Deep. Deep.

485
00:30:15,630 --> 00:30:17,347
- Mr Deep.
- I recognise you.

486
00:30:17,509 --> 00:30:19,784
The passed-out lady
Patrick carries around.

487
00:30:19,949 --> 00:30:21,667
Yes, that would be me.

488
00:30:23,269 --> 00:30:26,466
- I brought you a little something.
- Oh, how very thoughtful.

489
00:30:27,589 --> 00:30:29,579
Do we have to do this right now?

490
00:30:32,028 --> 00:30:33,541
Delicious.

491
00:30:33,708 --> 00:30:36,017
- It's not unlike a Ring Ding.
- What'd I tell you?

492
00:30:36,188 --> 00:30:38,702
I'm sure you'd really love
a glass of milk with that,

493
00:30:38,868 --> 00:30:41,301
but I have to get home
and changed for my book party.

494
00:30:41,467 --> 00:30:44,140
- If you don't mind...
- Don't rush. I'm a notary public.

495
00:30:44,307 --> 00:30:46,662
- I took a test.
- OK, I'm sorry.

496
00:30:46,827 --> 00:30:49,216
Um, how long do you
think this will take?

497
00:30:49,387 --> 00:30:51,218
Let's just review, hm?

498
00:30:52,307 --> 00:30:55,742
Signatures... check.

499
00:30:55,906 --> 00:31:00,377
Dates... check.

500
00:31:00,546 --> 00:31:03,014
My seal and you'll be
on your way in ten minutes.

501
00:31:03,186 --> 00:31:05,301
- Oh!
- An hour.

502
00:31:06,385 --> 00:31:08,296
A year.

503
00:31:08,465 --> 00:31:10,262
As long as it takes.
Who can say?

504
00:31:10,425 --> 00:31:13,303
Anything you can do to hurry?
I don't mind paying extra.

505
00:31:13,465 --> 00:31:17,821
- Trying to bribe a public official?
- Oh, this is ridiculous. I'm late!

506
00:31:17,984 --> 00:31:20,703
I'm late, and I'll send
a messenger in the morning.

507
00:31:20,864 --> 00:31:23,014
That will be more than enough time.

508
00:31:23,184 --> 00:31:26,221
- I could bring it by the office.
- Oh, no. I will send a messenger.

509
00:31:26,384 --> 00:31:29,216
Thank you, Mr Sullivan,
for your co-operation.

510
00:31:29,383 --> 00:31:32,295
Well, thank you for thanking me,
Mrs Sullivan.

511
00:31:33,423 --> 00:31:35,061
- A year?
- Patrick, I'm out. Out.

512
00:31:35,223 --> 00:31:37,896
You had your fun. This is too far.
You should be ashamed.

513
00:31:38,063 --> 00:31:40,815
- A nice lady like that?
- I wanted to give her a taste

514
00:31:40,982 --> 00:31:44,975
of her own medicine, period.
And then I... I don't know.

515
00:31:45,142 --> 00:31:48,896
- She's starting to grow on me.
- No. Look, no growing, OK?

516
00:31:49,062 --> 00:31:52,815
No growing on anyone by anyone.
No knees weakened,

517
00:31:52,981 --> 00:31:57,930
no shines taken to, none of it.
Not on my watch.

518
00:31:58,101 --> 00:32:02,413
Now, go. You and Ajay
have caused enough trouble.

519
00:32:03,541 --> 00:32:04,859
Out!

520
00:32:05,020 --> 00:32:07,011
[man] Dr Lloyd! This way, please!

521
00:32:07,180 --> 00:32:09,933
Dr Lloyd? This camera, please.

522
00:32:10,100 --> 00:32:13,331
- Smile, please.
- Beautiful, thank you.

523
00:32:13,500 --> 00:32:16,297
- Hi.
- [man] Eye contact, please?

524
00:32:16,459 --> 00:32:20,532
- Sign this.
- This way, please.

525
00:32:20,699 --> 00:32:23,008
- And where's Richard?
- Right over there.

526
00:32:23,179 --> 00:32:24,658
Thanks.

527
00:32:25,579 --> 00:32:27,535
- Hi! Oh!
- Not too shabby, huh?

528
00:32:27,698 --> 00:32:30,371
- It's wonderful. I can't believe it.
- Sign these.

529
00:32:30,538 --> 00:32:31,607
OK.

530
00:32:32,538 --> 00:32:35,132
- I have so much to tell you.
- Did you get the papers?

531
00:32:35,298 --> 00:32:38,973
- Um, they're at the notary.
- Excellent. Karl Bollenbecker's here.

532
00:32:39,138 --> 00:32:40,411
- Make that out to him.
- Oh?

533
00:32:40,577 --> 00:32:43,489
He wasn't coming, then his
office said he was. Good or bad?

534
00:32:43,657 --> 00:32:45,887
How could it be bad?
He hasn't even met you.

535
00:32:46,057 --> 00:32:48,093
- You look stunning.
- Thanks.

536
00:32:48,257 --> 00:32:50,691
- What happened to your head?
- Oh! Bird accident.

537
00:32:50,857 --> 00:32:53,689
A pigeon flew into me.
I'll go take care of it.

538
00:32:55,536 --> 00:32:59,245
- Emma? You remember Dr Benton?
- Yes, hi. Nice to see you. Hi, Judy.

539
00:33:05,295 --> 00:33:09,493
No sooner do we leave you then, bang,
I see your picture big on the bus.

540
00:33:09,655 --> 00:33:11,532
Oh! From the cake tasting!

541
00:33:11,695 --> 00:33:15,369
I felt so foolish, I went
and bought your book immediately.

542
00:33:15,534 --> 00:33:17,809
- Oh, that's unnecessary.
- Later I was reading

543
00:33:17,974 --> 00:33:22,013
your very sensible observation
and your clinical judgments...

544
00:33:22,174 --> 00:33:25,769
- Are they good things?
- I'm sure some people find them useful,

545
00:33:25,934 --> 00:33:29,687
but I was surprised that a helpless
romantic can give such practical advice.

546
00:33:29,853 --> 00:33:32,731
- [laughs] Me? Helpless?
- Oh, yes, you.

547
00:33:32,893 --> 00:33:35,202
Hopelessly helpless,
but let me finish.

548
00:33:35,373 --> 00:33:39,684
So my husband, Karl, returns
to the home and on top of his paper,

549
00:33:39,852 --> 00:33:44,607
there is an invitation to this
very party. Isn't it amazing?

550
00:33:44,772 --> 00:33:46,888
When you say Karl,
do you mean Karl...

551
00:33:47,052 --> 00:33:48,690
- [both] Bollenbecker.
- [gasps]

552
00:33:48,852 --> 00:33:52,480
- It's a small world, isn't it?
- Yes!

553
00:33:52,651 --> 00:33:56,439
Teeny. Like a marble.
Or a gumball.

554
00:33:56,611 --> 00:33:59,205
I had to drag Karl
by the ear to come here.

555
00:33:59,371 --> 00:34:01,566
- It is a girly book.
- Oh, no. It's not that.

556
00:34:01,731 --> 00:34:05,439
Karl can be very girly. Only that he
doesn't like to socialise with someone

557
00:34:05,610 --> 00:34:10,320
- whose company he intends to liquidate.
- Liquidate?

558
00:34:10,490 --> 00:34:13,880
- Who, Richard?
- Yes, but we can fix that.

559
00:34:14,050 --> 00:34:17,724
After this party, you and Richard
will join us for dinner.

560
00:34:17,889 --> 00:34:23,043
If Karl sees the man I saw,
Abdington Books will be safe, I'm sure.

561
00:34:23,209 --> 00:34:27,281
That is unbelievably kind of you,

562
00:34:27,448 --> 00:34:30,645
but you see, Richard and I made plans
and so we're supposed to...

563
00:34:30,808 --> 00:34:32,958
Only one thing
you're supposed to do, Emma,

564
00:34:33,128 --> 00:34:37,838
and it's to bring your fiancé to dinner.
Let's find Richard. Karl is waiting.

565
00:34:42,447 --> 00:34:46,360
Oh! Oh, oh, my husband hates you,
but you saved our marriage. Do you mind?

566
00:34:46,527 --> 00:34:48,518
Not at all.
Um, who shall I make it out to?

567
00:34:48,687 --> 00:34:50,120
- To...
- Richard!

568
00:34:53,686 --> 00:34:57,042
Um... thank you.

569
00:34:58,206 --> 00:35:00,197
Oh, hey, hey.
I brought your papers.

570
00:35:00,366 --> 00:35:04,517
Richard! Sweetheart.
Please go with me on this, OK?

571
00:35:04,685 --> 00:35:06,880
- Remember Greta Bollenbecker?
- Cake lady!

572
00:35:07,045 --> 00:35:11,243
- [laughs] It's a small world.
- So small. Constantly shrinking.

573
00:35:11,405 --> 00:35:14,044
- It must be the global warming.
- I want to introduce you

574
00:35:14,204 --> 00:35:16,593
- to my husband.
- Her husband, Karl,

575
00:35:16,764 --> 00:35:19,483
is Karl Bollenbecker,
who just acquired Richard's,

576
00:35:19,644 --> 00:35:23,193
your publishing house and he's thinking
of dumping you, Richard, and it.

577
00:35:23,364 --> 00:35:26,435
- Wait, I own a publishing house?
- Yes, and you're my fiancé,

578
00:35:26,603 --> 00:35:29,800
so please just focus, concentrate.
Got it?

579
00:35:29,963 --> 00:35:32,397
- This is him.
- [laughs]

580
00:35:32,563 --> 00:35:35,521
- You must be the cake dunker.
- You got me.

581
00:35:35,683 --> 00:35:39,800
- That's my Richard!
- Casual Fridays?

582
00:35:39,962 --> 00:35:42,112
I actually just came
from soccer practise.

583
00:35:42,282 --> 00:35:45,160
- You play football?
- Well, I'm no Lucas Podolski.

584
00:35:45,322 --> 00:35:48,473
Podolski! [laughs]
Well, nothing could beat Podolski!

585
00:35:48,642 --> 00:35:52,759
I own his team and he is a magnificent
pain in the ass, but a genius.

586
00:35:52,921 --> 00:35:55,196
- [laughs]
- You own the Bayern München club?

587
00:35:55,361 --> 00:35:58,592
Why don't you use Klose on defence?
He's been under-utilised.

588
00:35:58,761 --> 00:36:01,797
- That's what I told that stupid coach.
- Klinsmann? Gotta go.

589
00:36:01,960 --> 00:36:05,316
- We agree. [laughs]
- Excuse me. My name's... Ow! Jesus!

590
00:36:05,480 --> 00:36:07,038
- What?
- Hand noogies!

591
00:36:07,200 --> 00:36:11,716
We give each other hand noogies.
This is my brother, Carl.

592
00:36:11,880 --> 00:36:14,871
Your name is Carl as well?
This is a small world!

593
00:36:15,039 --> 00:36:19,396
Yes, teeny! Like a gimlet. Yes, my tiny,
teeny little brother, but not small.

594
00:36:19,559 --> 00:36:22,710
No. Big. Older, but not by much.

595
00:36:22,879 --> 00:36:26,473
- Carl, who I love so very, very much.
- How's it goin', bro?

596
00:36:26,638 --> 00:36:30,551
- Wine?
- I'm sorry, I'm suddenly very thirsty.

597
00:36:30,718 --> 00:36:33,949
- Carl? Carl?
- [whispers] Carl.

598
00:36:34,118 --> 00:36:36,871
This is Karl Bollenbecker
and I'm Greta, his wife,

599
00:36:37,038 --> 00:36:41,747
- and we're so charmed by your sister.
- And her outspoken fiancé

600
00:36:41,917 --> 00:36:45,114
<i>who seems to find fault with
every player in the Bundesliga.</i>

601
00:36:45,277 --> 00:36:49,190
- But not Podolski.
- [laughs] But never Podolski!

602
00:36:50,516 --> 00:36:52,984
So, you sound English,
but your sister...

603
00:36:53,156 --> 00:36:56,512
- Can I borrow Emma?
- Yes, but we both had... I'm sorry.

604
00:36:56,676 --> 00:36:59,873
- [screams]
- [both] A hand noogie! [laughing]

605
00:37:00,916 --> 00:37:03,065
Who is that man out there
pretending to be me?

606
00:37:03,235 --> 00:37:05,305
- I can explain.
- He's wearing sweatpants.

607
00:37:05,475 --> 00:37:08,308
- Sullivan! Honey, you're stress-eating.
- I'm not. Go on.

608
00:37:08,475 --> 00:37:11,751
I wasn't at my father's. I was with
Sullivan. Not "with him" with him,

609
00:37:11,915 --> 00:37:15,987
but in his apartment drunk. That sounds
worse. I assure you I was fully clothed.

610
00:37:16,154 --> 00:37:18,827
Beyond that, I'm not certain,
except he showed up today

611
00:37:18,994 --> 00:37:21,030
with papers when I had
to go to the tasting,

612
00:37:21,194 --> 00:37:23,424
which you refused to go
because you're busy...

613
00:37:23,594 --> 00:37:26,187
- Get back to the Bollenbeckers!
- Right. Fine.

614
00:37:26,353 --> 00:37:29,265
At the cake tasting,
there was this sweet lady.

615
00:37:29,433 --> 00:37:33,870
And she thought Sullivan was my fiancé
and I just couldn't disappoint her.

616
00:37:34,033 --> 00:37:37,661
But this lady wasn't sweet at all.
She was Mrs Bollenbecker,

617
00:37:37,832 --> 00:37:40,141
- which I didn't know.
- You certainly know now!

618
00:37:40,312 --> 00:37:43,384
I do. Had I known I wouldn't
have let the whole thing continue.

619
00:37:43,552 --> 00:37:46,703
But it did continue until everyone
was quite taken with him,

620
00:37:46,872 --> 00:37:49,510
especially Mrs Bollenbecker
when he sang.

621
00:37:49,671 --> 00:37:51,980
- He's a singer?
- No, no, no. He's a fireman.

622
00:37:52,151 --> 00:37:57,271
- Darling, are you sure you want that?
- Yes. Yes, I am. What is he doing here?

623
00:37:57,431 --> 00:37:59,899
He came to bring me
the notarised papers.

624
00:38:00,071 --> 00:38:04,586
But then there was Mrs Bollenbecker.
I'm Emma Lloyd, so he's my fiancé.

625
00:38:04,750 --> 00:38:09,187
- And I am tiny brother Carl.
- Oh, Richard, I'm terribly sorry.

626
00:38:09,350 --> 00:38:12,501
But, uh, oh, look! Mini-cupcakes.

627
00:38:12,669 --> 00:38:15,388
Look, Emma. I only got
about half of what you're saying,

628
00:38:15,549 --> 00:38:18,427
but this seems to be something
that can be cleaned up easily.

629
00:38:18,589 --> 00:38:22,218
So before you harpoon what is left of my
reputation, I am gonna go in there...

630
00:38:22,389 --> 00:38:25,107
No, no, no, you can't!
They're going to exterminate you.

631
00:38:25,268 --> 00:38:27,907
- What?
- Not you, Abdington Books.

632
00:38:28,068 --> 00:38:31,504
Terminate! No, liquidate! That's it.
Yes, chop it up in little pieces,

633
00:38:31,668 --> 00:38:35,377
sell it all off! Everything must go!
That's why Karl wasn't coming.

634
00:38:35,548 --> 00:38:37,902
- But he did come!
- Because Mrs B made him come.

635
00:38:38,067 --> 00:38:40,535
She made him come so he could meet you.

636
00:38:40,707 --> 00:38:44,859
Oh, look. I think he's
really starting to like you.

637
00:38:45,027 --> 00:38:47,587
Oh, all right, I...
Let me think now.

638
00:38:47,747 --> 00:38:50,897
Man owns so many entities, I can buy
a year before our paths cross,

639
00:38:51,066 --> 00:38:53,819
so we just have to get through this.
A few more minutes?

640
00:38:53,986 --> 00:38:58,821
And a dinner. Tonight. It was Mrs B's
idea, so Karl could get to know you.

641
00:38:58,986 --> 00:39:00,259
- He's gone.
- Karl?

642
00:39:00,425 --> 00:39:02,541
- No, Sullivan. He's gone.
- But the dinner!

643
00:39:02,705 --> 00:39:06,618
- Get him there!
- Oh, uh...

644
00:39:09,985 --> 00:39:12,862
- Is Sullivan even in here?
- I don't see how he'd fit.

645
00:39:13,024 --> 00:39:15,094
Not now, Marcy.

646
00:39:17,624 --> 00:39:20,343
- Find the lioness within.
- Now, you've read my book?

647
00:39:20,504 --> 00:39:24,098
<i>- [vibrating]
- Mr Sullivan, Emma Lloyd here.</i>

648
00:39:24,263 --> 00:39:25,332
Here's the deal.

649
00:39:25,503 --> 00:39:30,702
My entire career, and my marriage to
Richard, probably, are at stake here.

650
00:39:32,343 --> 00:39:37,132
Frankly, I need you.
I really need you... tonight.

651
00:39:37,302 --> 00:39:42,695
- [laughing]
- [speaking in German]

652
00:39:50,141 --> 00:39:52,132
<i>[cell phone rings]</i>

653
00:39:53,821 --> 00:39:56,051
<i>- Hello?
- [Richard] Say "yes" if he's there,</i>

654
00:39:56,221 --> 00:39:58,940
<i>- "Oh, my God" if he's not.
- Oh, my God.</i>

